{
  "texts": [
    "Gate Recurrent Unit (GRU) is considered as a gating mechanism in RNNs, where the original reset gate is maintained, while the forget gate and input gate are combined into the update gate.",
    "GRU does not require any extra memory units, because an update gate has the ability to regulate the amount of data that must be obtained from the candidate state for the current state and retained from the historical state Cho et al (2014).",
    "Because there are fewer gate structures in GRU, it has a simple structure, fewer parameters, and requires less processing.",
    "As a result, GRU can produce good performance while shortening the model training process and avoiding overfitting issues.",
    "Only one study has been reviewed He et al (2020) that used the GRU architecture for predicting student's academic performance and achieved a reasonable prediction accuracy of about 80%."
  ]
}